To quickly and significantly adjust the AutoLion battery capacity to match the experimental value when there is a mismatch, follow these steps:

---

### ✅ **Step-by-Step Solution:**

#### 1. **Identify the Mismatch**
- Open the **"Voltage" monitor** in GT-POST.
- Compare the **AutoLion voltage vs. capacity plot** with the **experimental data**.
- Observe the **capacity mismatch** (e.g., the AutoLion curve appears "stretched" in time).

---

#### 2. **Adjust the Cathode Capacity Loading**
- **Go back to GT-ISE** and double-click on the **AutoLion part**.
- Navigate to the **"Cathode" folder**.
- Locate the **"Capacity Loading" attribute**.
- Define a **new parameter** for this attribute, e.g., `[CathodeLoading]`.

---

#### 3. **Set Up a Parameter Sweep in Case Setup**
- In **Case Setup**, click the **"Add Parameter"** button.
- Create a new parameter named **`[CathodeLoading]`**.
- Click the **"Append Cases"** button 9 times or use the **"Append Multiple Cases"** option.
- Sweep the **`[CathodeLoading]`** attribute from **3.0 to 3.9 mAh/cm²** in increments of **0.1**.
- Set the **"Case Label"** to **`[CathodeLoading] mAh/cm²`**.

---

#### 4. **Run the Model and Analyze Results**
- Run the model.
- In the **Monitor**, observe the **voltage vs. capacity** plots for each case.
- Identify the **case** where the **AutoLion curve most closely matches the experimental data**.

---

#### 5. **Select the Best-Fit Capacity Loading Value**
- Go back to **Case Setup**.
- Delete the **9 extra cases** and keep only the **best-fit case** (e.g., **3.3 mAh/cm²**).
- Set the **`[CathodeLoading]`** parameter to the best-fit value.

---

#### 6. **Promote Key Parameters for Further Calibration**
- Promote other key parameters such as:
  - **N/P Ratio**
  - **First Charge Capacity**
  - **First Discharge Capacity**
  - **Umax**
  - **Initial SOC**
- These parameters affect the **cell balance** and **OCV** and are critical for accurate calibration.

---

#### 7. **Use the Design Optimizer for Fine-Tuning**
- Open the **Design Optimizer**.
- Select the **"Integrated Design Optimizer"**.
- Choose the **"Transient Targeting"** option.
- Define the **"Signal or Time RLT"** as the **"Voltage"** output signal.
- Define the **"Target Profile"** as the **experimental voltage profile**.
- Set the **"Term Weight"** to prioritize the **voltage error**.
- Run the optimization to **minimize the RMS error** between the simulation and experimental data.

---

### ✅ **Summary of Key Actions:**
| Step | Action |
|------|--------|
| 1 | Compare voltage vs. capacity plots |
| 2 | Adjust **Cathode Capacity Loading** |
| 3 | Set up a **parameter sweep** in Case Setup |
| 4 | Run the model and analyze results |
| 5 | Select the best-fit **Capacity Loading** value |
| 6 | Promote key parameters for cell balance |
| 7 | Use the **Design Optimizer** to fine-tune the model |

---

### ✅ **Why This Works:**
- The **Cathode Capacity Loading** directly affects the **total capacity** of the cell.
- By adjusting this parameter and using the **Design Optimizer**, you can **quickly align** the **AutoLion model** with the **experimental data**.
- This approach is **efficient** and **effective** for **quick calibration** of the **capacity** in AutoLion.

---

### ✅ **Final Tip:**
- Always **validate** the results in the **.glx file** and **compare** the **SOH** and **voltage** plots to ensure the model is **accurately calibrated**.
